<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-601-444  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 601 444.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  June 18 1990 v11 n25 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MIS must play a bigger role in facilities management;decentralization dilutes the ability to oversee data processingsites.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Puttre, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Dispersed data processing facilities can be a problem for MISmanagers who are responsible for the costs associated withdowntime.andP;  Distributed facilities management is necessary fordistributed computer processing.andP;  Between 1980 and 1990 computerdowntime incurred through facilities mismanagement grew from 3percent of total processing downtime to 28 percent of totalprocessing downtime, according to Computersite Engineering inCambridge, MA.andP;  Increased power outages associated with summertemperatures and the use of air conditioners compound the MISmanagers' problem of too much downtime, especially in situationswhere essential services such as water and power are handled bydisinterested parties.andP;  Written service-level agreements thatspecify required power levels can help the situation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MISDecentralizationFacility ManagementData ProcessingMismanagement.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Mismanagement of the site infrastructure accounts for somedowntime. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>